 East Yorkshire called Cave, apparently from a river name derived from Old English <i>cāf</i> ‘swift’.","English (of Norman origin): nickname from Norman and Picard Old French <i>cauf</i> (from Latin <i>calvus</i>) ‘bald’.","French: topographic name for someone who lived in or near a cave, from Old French <i>cave</i> ‘cave’, ‘cellar’ (from Latin <i>cavea</i>, a derivative of <i>cavus</i> ‘hollow’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Cavin","meanings":["Scottish (Wigtownshire): variant of <b>Caveen</b>, a shortened form of Manx <i>Mac Dhaimhín</i>, son of <i>Daimhín</i>. The personal name is a diminutive of Gaelic <i>damh</i> ‘bard, poet’.","French: diminutive of   Cave  ."]},{"name":"Caves","meanings":["English: variant of   Cave  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Keeve","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Cave  . This surname is rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Chaffee","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): descriptive nickname from a derivative of Old French <i>chauf</i> ‘bald’ (from Latin <i>calvus</i>). Compare   Cave  ."]},{"name":"Cavett","meanings":["Scottish (of French origin): altered form of French <b>Cavet</b>, which is either a diminutive of   Cave   3 or a metonymic occupational name for a laborer, one who used a <i>cavet</i>, an Old Occitan word for a tool for clearing ground for cultivation."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":6,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":37,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":62,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Peter de Cave was born in 1253, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Geoffrey de Cave, was 18 and his mother, Mabel de Talso, was 33. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Elena Bromfiete. He died in 1326, at the age of 73."},"et":{"1253–1326":"1253–1326","1255–Male":"1255–Surnud","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1270–1318":"1270–1318","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1235–1312":"1235–1312","1220–1244":"1220–1244","1253":"1253","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1326":"1326","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1312":"1312","1235":"1235","1244"